# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arnold-hague
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The **36th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 36 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It crosses Africa, the Mediterranean Sea, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] In the ancient Mediterranean world, its role for navigation and geography was similar to that played by the Equator today.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] From 7 April 1991 to 31 December 1996, the parallel defined the limit of the northern no-fly zone in Iraq.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 36 minutes during the summer solstice and 9 hours, 43 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] In the United States, the 36th parallel north is occasionally used as a rough northern boundary for the Sun Belt, a region spanning most Southern and Southwestern states and comprising most of the nation's warmest climates.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel helped define the North Carolina–Tennessee–Virginia Corners.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The sixth standard parallel south of Mount Diablo Range at 35°48′ north, 13.8344 miles south of the 36th parallel, forms a continuous boundary between the California counties of Monterey, Kings, Tulare, and Inyo on the north and the counties of San Luis Obispo, Kern, and San Bernardino on the south.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It is sometimes taken as the boundary between Central California and Southern California.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel 36° north approximately forms the southernmost boundary of the Missouri Bootheel with the State of Arkansas.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The 36th parallel passes through Duke University in several places.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Its Campus Drive that connects the campuses crosses the parallel several times.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The Duke Gardens has a "36th Parallel Club" although the garden itself is just north of the parallel.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The **37th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 37 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It crosses Europe, the Mediterranean Sea, Africa, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the Sun is visible for 14 hours, 42 minutes during the summer solstice and 9 hours, 37 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The 37th parallel north is roughly the northern limit of the visibility of Canopus, the second-brightest star of the night sky.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Along with the 37th parallel south, it is the latitude at which solar irradiance is closest to the planetary average, with higher solar irradiance equatorward and lower poleward.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] In the United States, the parallel defines the southern borders of Utah, Colorado, and Kansas, and the northern borders of Arizona, New Mexico, and Oklahoma.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It dates to the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854 when Congress divided Unorganized Territory into Kansas and Nebraska north of the 37th parallel and a remainder Indian Territory to the south.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Before that, the line had been thought to be the boundary between the Cherokee and Osage reservations – the 2.46 miles (3.96 km) discrepancy resulting in the creation of the Cherokee Strip.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Congress extended the line west to New Mexico Territory, thus defining which states and territories would constitute The South between the Colorado and Mississippi Rivers, and creating what later became the Oklahoma Panhandle.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel 37° north formed the southern boundary of the historic and extralegal Territory of Jefferson.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The **38th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 38 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It crosses Europe, the Mediterranean Sea, Asia, the Pacific Ocean, North America, and the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The 38th parallel north formed the border between North and South Korea prior to the Korean War.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] At this latitude, the Sun is visible for 14 hours, 48 minutes during the summer solstice and 9 hours, 32 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] From 1910 to 1945, Korea was ruled by the Empire of Japan as a colony.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] This parallel divided the Korean peninsula roughly in the middle.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] In 1948, this parallel became the boundary between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (North Korea) and the Republic of Korea (South Korea), both of which claim to be the government of the whole of Korea.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] On 25 June 1950, after a series of cross-border raids and gunfire from both the Northern and the Southern sides, the North Korean Army crossed the 38th parallel and invaded South Korea.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] After the Armistice agreement was signed on July 27, 1953, a new line was established to separate North Korea and South Korea.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] This Military Demarcation Line is surrounded by a Demilitarized Zone (DMZ).
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The demarcation line crosses the 38th parallel, from the southwest to the northeast.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The **39th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 39 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 14 hours, 54 minutes during the summer solstice and 9 hours, 26 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Daylight along the 39th parallel north falls under 10 hours a day starting on 18 November and returns to over ten hours a day beginning 24 January.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The growth of crops and other plants is considerably slowed during this period of reduced sunlight.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The intersection of the 120th meridian and 39th parallel is in Lake Tahoe.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The **40th parallel north** is a circle of latitude that is 40 degrees north of the Earth's equatorial plane.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] At this latitude the sun is visible for 15 hours, 1 minute and 28 seconds during the summer solstice and 9 hours, 20 minutes during the winter solstice.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] On 21 June, the maximum altitude of the sun is 73.44 degrees, while it is 26.56 degrees on 21 December.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The maximum altitude of the Sun is > 35.00º in October and > 28.00º in November.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The 40th parallel north is the southern baseline for Canada's National Topographic System.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel 40° north formed the boundary between the Kansas and Nebraska territories, as per the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It remains the boundary between the modern states of Kansas and Nebraska.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel 40° north formed the original northern boundary of the British Colony of Maryland.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] A subsequent royal grant gave the Colony of Pennsylvania land north of the 40th parallel but mistakenly assumed it would intersect the Twelve Mile Circle, which it does not.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Pennsylvania's border was thus unclear and the colony pushed for a border far south of the 40th parallel.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The Mason–Dixon Line was drawn between 1763 and 1767 as the compromise boundary between the overlapping claims of these two colonies.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel 40° north passes through the cities of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, Boulder, Colorado, and Columbus, Ohio; as well as northern suburbs of Indianapolis, Indiana and the southern suburbs of Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] The parallel goes directly through the John Glenn Columbus International Airport, with runway 10L-28R lying immediately north of the line, runway 10R-28L lying slightly south of it, and the line going through the northernmost edges of the terminal.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] It also passes through the main campus of The Ohio State University; specifically, it cuts directly across the Oval greenspace, between University Hall and the William Oxley Thompson Memorial Library.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Ohio Stadium, one of the largest stadiums in the world, barely misses the parallel 40° north (6 seconds or 185 metres (607 ft) above 40° north).
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Baseline Road in Boulder, Colorado, traces the parallel 40° north.
[src:arnold-hague/40th-parallel-north] Thistle, Utah, a ghost town since 1983, is slightly (30 seconds or 956 metres (0.594 mi)) below 40° north.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The **University of Aberdeen** (abbreviated ***Aberd.*** in post-nominals; Scottish Gaelic: *Oilthigh Obar Dheathain*) is a public research university in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was founded in 1495 when William Elphinstone, Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland, petitioned Pope Alexander VI on behalf of King James IV to establish King's College, making it one of Scotland's four ancient universities and the fifth-oldest university in the English-speaking world.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Along with the universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, and Edinburgh, the university was part of the Scottish Enlightenment during the 18th century.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university as it is currently constituted was formed in 1860 by a merger between King's College and Marischal College, a second university founded in 1593 as a Protestant alternative to the former.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's iconic buildings act as symbols of wider Aberdeen, particularly Marischal College in the city centre and the crown steeple of King's College in Old Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] There are two campuses; the predominantly utilised King's College campus dominates the section of the city known as Old Aberdeen, which is approximately two miles north of the city centre.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Although the original site of the university's foundation, most academic buildings apart from the King's College Chapel and Quadrangle were constructed in the 20th century during a period of significant expansion.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's Foresterhill campus is next to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary and houses the School of Medicine and Dentistry as well as the School of Medical Sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Together these buildings form one of Europe's largest health campuses.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The annual income of the institution for 2024–25 was £257.2 million of which £54.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £262.5 million.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen has educated a wide range of notable alumni, and the university played key roles in the Scottish Reformation, Scottish Enlightenment, and the Scottish Renaissance.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Five Nobel laureates have since been associated with the university: two in Chemistry, one in Physiology or Medicine, one in Physics, and one in Peace.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] There appears to have existed in Old Aberdeen, from a very early period, a *studium generate,* or university, attached to the episcopal chapter of the See of Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It seems that James was keen to ensure that Scotland had as many universities as England at the time, and it was to possess all the privileges enjoyed by those of Paris and Bologna, two of the most highly favoured in Europe.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university, modelled on that of the University of Paris and intended principally as a law school, soon became the most famous and popular of the Scots seats of learning, largely due to the prestige of Elphinstone and his friend, Hector Boece, the first principal appointed in 1500.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Its aim was to train doctors, teachers and clergy who would serve the communities of northern Scotland, as well as lawyers and administrators for the Scottish Crown.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was a collegiate foundation with 36 full-time staff and students and walls protecting it from the outside world.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In 1497 the college established the first chair of medicine in the English-speaking world.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The first book (there was no printing press in Scotland at the time) to be printed in Edinburgh and in Scotland was the Aberdeen Breviary, which was written by both Elphinstone and Boece in 1509.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the Scottish Reformation in 1560, King's College was purged of its Roman Catholic staff but in other respects was largely resistant to change.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] George Keith, the fifth Earl Marischal, was a moderniser within the college and supportive of the reforming ideas of Peter Ramus and Andrew Melville.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In April 1593 he founded a second university in the 'New Town', Marischal College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is also possible the founding of the Fraserburgh University in nearby Fraserburgh by Sir Alexander Fraser, a business rival of Keith, was instrumental in its creation.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen was highly unusual at this time for having two universities in one city: as 20th-century university prospectuses observed, Aberdeen had the same number as existed in England at the time (the University of Oxford and University of Cambridge).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Initially, Marischal College offered the principal of King's College a role in selecting its academics, but this was refused – the first blow in a developing rivalry.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Marischal College, in the commercial heart of the city (rather than the ancient but much smaller collegiate enclave of Old Aberdeen), was quite different in nature and outlook.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] For example, it was more integrated into the life of the city, such as allowing students to live outwith the college.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The two rival colleges often clashed, sometimes in court, but also in brawls between students on the streets of Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Duncan Liddell endowed the first chair in mathematics at Marischal College in 1613, but the first professor was not appointed until 1626.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] As the institutions put aside their differences, a process of attempted (but unsuccessful) mergers began in the 17th century.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] During this time, both colleges made notable intellectual contributions to the Scottish Enlightenment.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Both colleges supported the Jacobite rebellion and following the defeat of the 1715 rising were largely purged by the authorities of their academics and officials.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The nearest the two colleges had come to full union was as the Caroline University of Aberdeen, a merger initiated by Charles I in 1641, which united the two colleges for twenty years.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the civil conflicts of the Wars of the Three Kingdoms, a more complete unification was attempted following the ratification of Parliament by Oliver Cromwell during the interregnum in 1654.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This united university survived until the Restoration whereby all laws made during this period were rescinded by Charles II and the two colleges reverted to independent status.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Charles I is still recognised as one of the university's founders, due to his part in creating the Caroline University and his benevolence towards King's College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Aberdeen Philosophical Society (known locally as the Wise Club) was created by Thomas Reid, George Campbell, David Skene, John Gregory, John Stewart, and Robert Traill, and held its first meeting in the Old Red Lion Inn on 12 January 1758.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] From its inception, the society was an intimate, private body whose members were drawn exclusively from the learned professions, and this feature differentiated it from the more open and socially inclusive societies like the Glasgow Literary Society or the Select Society of Edinburgh.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Over 133 papers were given and discussed at the meeting, and many of these formed the basis of books subsequently published.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The society was eventually disbanded in March 1773.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The society and its individual members played a key role in the Scottish Enlightenment, and it was the most important forum for the promotion of enlightened thought and values in Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Free Church of Scotland founded Christ's College in Aberdeen in 1843 for the training of ministers.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] An extravagant Gothic building, with a commanding oriel window and tower, was erected for the college at the western end of Union Street in 1850.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Linked to the college was a museum and library (containing 17,000 volumes).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the church reunion of 1929, Christ's College became a Church of Scotland college and was integrated into the University of Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The college building is no longer used by either the church or the university, and the college is contained completely within the buildings of King's College, maintaining its own divinity library.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university hosted its first meeting of the British Science Association in 1859.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Having no suitable meeting place to host the meeting, the town raised the money themselves by personal subscription and built the Music Hall.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was capable of holding about 2,500 people and so successful was the meeting that associate membership, necessary to gain access to the proceedings, had to be capped.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Prominent among the local organisers were Professors James Clerk Maxwell (Natural Philosophy) and James Nicol (Geology) of Marischal College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Prince Albert, the Prince Consort, took on the role of president for the year.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The young Maxwell himself, still only 28, spoke on three different subjects, one being a presentation of his newly discovered law of molecular velocities in a gas.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The 'Maxwell distribution law', as it is now known, is the law of physics with the strongest Aberdeen connection.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition, Sir Charles Lyell, president of the Geological Section of the British Academy, and a champion of Charles Darwin's work, made one of the first announcements that Darwin had undertaken a body of work on evolution and was about to release his findings.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The organisers felt that they might be risking something in holding the meeting much further north than they had done before but in the event the Aberdeen meeting was the most well attended the BA had ever had.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Further unsuccessful suggestions for union were brought about throughout the 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] William Ogilvie, known as the Rebel Professor, proposed a paper on the union and reform of the two colleges in 1787, but the proposals were rejected by seven (known as the 'seven wise Masters') out of ten professors at King's.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The evolving examination system and university research now required much higher academic standards from the students.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The two colleges in Aberdeen merged on 15 September 1860 in accordance with the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858, which also created a new medical school at Marischal College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The 1858 Act of Parliament stated the "*united University shall take rank among the Universities of Scotland as from the date of erection of King's College and University.*" The university is thus Scotland's third oldest and the United Kingdom's fifth oldest university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The transference of the arts classes from Marischal to King's College required the extension of King's at the cost of £20,000.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This included the rebuilding of two sides of the quadrangle for the class-rooms (1862) and the erection of the library (1870), which for many years had occupied the nave of the chapel.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In 1873, university students voted against university degrees being open to women.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] However, all faculties were open to women in 1892, and in 1894 the first 20 matriculated females began their studies at the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Four women graduated in arts by 1898, and by the following year, women made up a quarter of the faculty.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The closing of the quadrangle of Marischal College was completed during the university's quatercentenary in 1906, which was officially opened by Edward VII and Alexandra, and which saw some of the most extravagant celebrations and expressions of civic pride ever demonstrated in Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Four days of festivities took place across the city, which included church services, banquets, torchlight processions, and fireworks displays.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In all, the cost of the four days of festivities was the modern equivalent of £1.34 million.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The ceremony saw the granting of honorary degrees to over a hundred public and academic figures from across the academic world.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In an extravagant display of luxury, Lord Strathcona, the then chancellor of the university, spent £8518 in entertaining around 2500 invited guests in a tent specially designed for the occasion.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] After having received an honorary degree (LLD) in 1905, Thomas Hardy celebrated Aberdeen as 'a university which can claim in my opinion to an exceptional degree that breadth of view & openness of mind that all Universities profess to cultivate, but many stifle'.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Hardy wrote a poem for a special number of the student publication, *Alma Mater*, in celebration of the quatercentenary of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 20th century, the university expanded greatly, particularly at King's College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] New buildings were constructed on the land around King's College throughout the 20th century.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Initially, these were built to match the ancient buildings (e.g. the New King's lecture rooms and Elphinstone Hall), but later ones from the 1960s onward were constructed in brutalist style.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Meanwhile, the Foresterhill campus began to train medical students in the 1930s next to Aberdeen Royal Infirmary.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Following extensive fundraising, a £57 million new university library (the Sir Duncan Rice Library) opened in autumn 2011 at the King's College campus to replace the outgrown Queen Mother Library and was officially opened by the Queen in September 2012.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Today, most students spend most of their time in modern buildings which provide up-to-date facilities for teaching, research and other activities such as dining.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] However, the old buildings at King's College are still in use as lecture and tutorial rooms and accommodation for various academic departments.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In February 2020, the Scottish Funding Council (SFC) found that in approving a financial settlement agreement with the former principal Sir Ian Diamond, the university failed to make best use of public funds or exercise good governance.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] As a result of the investigation, the university was ordered to repay £119,000 of grant finance to the SFC and undertake an externally facilitated examination of its governance and culture.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] On 5 December 2023 it was announced that a working group, chaired by Professor Karl Leydecker, had been set up to look at the future of teaching of modern languages at the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was looking at three options, "all of which involve the end of single honours French, Gaelic, German and Spanish", and was engaging in consultation with student and faculty.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was stated that departmental "income does not cover even the direct costs of staff delivering Modern Languages provision before any central costs ... leading to a projected deficit for Modern Languages of £1.64m in 2023/24." The financial statements were contested by staff and UCU.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] At an online meeting of the University Senate on 6 December, senators voted 78–15 in favour of a motion which "called for an immediate halt in the consultation process until an overall plan is presented in detail to Senate for appropriate scrutiny." Five senators abstained.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] On 8 December, *The Gaudie* reported that staff had been sent 'Risk of Redundancy' letters which stated that staff who are made redundant would receive four months pay.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A group of academics from the department released a statement which described the proposed changes as "institutional vandalism".
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A public petition to save Modern Languages gained over 18,600 signatures.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] After the submission of two motions calling to protect languages degrees at the University of Aberdeen, a debate took place in Scottish Parliament, where the university was urged to explore alternative options.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] EU consulates also spoke out in favour of the languages programmes., as well as scome of Scotland's best-known folk music starts.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The local UCU branch successfully balloted for strike action at the university, in support of Modern Languages degrees.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Staff-led business proposals were positively received and the consultation on Modern Languages was ended in March 2024 with the removal of risk of compulsory redundancies.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's main campus is at King's College in Old Aberdeen, where the original buildings are still in use in addition to many 20th-century buildings.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A second campus at Foresterhill accommodates the School of Medicine, Medical Science and Nutrition.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition, there are smaller facilities at other sites such as the Royal Cornhill Hospital to the west of the city centre, and the Rowett Institute in Bucksburn.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The King's College campus covers an area of some 35 hectares around the ancient King's College buildings and the High Street.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It hosts around two-thirds of the university's built estate and most student facilities, and lies 2 miles north of Aberdeen city centre.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university does not own all the buildings on the "campus" which also include private houses, shops and businesses (although many of these rely heavily on custom from the university community) and it is best thought of as a district of the city dominated by the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It can be reached from the city centre by bus routes 1, 2, 13, 19 and 20 operated by First Aberdeen and from northern Aberdeenshire or Aberdeen bus station by various routes operated by Stagecoach Bluebird.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The historic King's College buildings form a quadrangle with an interior court, two sides of which have been rebuilt and expanded with a library wing in the 19th century.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Crown Tower and the chapel, the oldest parts, date from around 1500.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The original foundation contained the chapel, the Great Hall and living accommodation, with its own kitchen and brewery, a well in the quadrangle, and a college garden to provide herbs and vegetables.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Grammar School was just outside the walls, in front of the college.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Crown Tower is surmounted by a structure about 40 ft (12 m) high, consisting of a six-sided lantern and Imperial crown, both sculptured, and resting on the intersections of two arched ornamental slips rising from the four corners of the top of the tower.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This crown, also known as the "Crown of Kings", frequently acts as a symbol of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The choir of the chapel contains original oak-canopied stalls, miserere seats, and lofty open screens in the French flamboyant style.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] They were preserved by the college's Principal during the Reformation, who fought off local barons who had attacked the nearby St Machar's Cathedral.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Cromwell Tower, created between 1658 and 1662 opposite the Crown Tower, was originally built as residential accommodation, but an observatory was built on top in 1826.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The library wing was converted into an exhibition and conference venue in the 1990s and today also houses the university's Business School.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The first of the modern age of construction in the King's campus began with the construction in 1913 of the New Building (now known as *"New King's"*), largely in a similar architectural style to the old buildings.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A large manse located on the lawn opposite King's College was removed before the First World War.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] New King's groups to form a yet larger quadrangle-like green for the campus also bordered by the High Street, King's and Elphinstone Hall, a traditional 1930 replacement for the Great Hall.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Elphinstone Hall was subsequently used as a dining facility but is now used for graduations, examinations, fairs, and other large university events.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] However, most students and staff spend relatively little time in these historic buildings, with a large number of modern ones housing most facilities and academic departments.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Most date from the second half of the 20th century.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Some of these echo the existing architecture of Old Aberdeen, such as the Fraser Noble Building with its distinctive concrete crown designed to resemble the one adorning King's College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Other buildings were constructed of stone in the 1950s (e.g. the Taylor Building and Meston Building).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A number of other buildings are designed in the brutalist style, such as the Arts Lecture Theatre and adjoining William Guild Building, opened in 1969 to house the School of Psychology.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Also on the site is the Cruickshank Botanic Garden which was presented to the university in 1899 and is open to the public.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Powis Gateway forms the east gate and archway from College Bounds, Old Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] These oriental style towers with minarets have provoked much interest over the years.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] At one time there was a portrait of John Leslie dressed in Turkish costume, on the walls of Powis House, but there is no obvious connection between the estate and the Middle East.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The gateway is also adorned with panels bearing the coats of arms of the Lairds of Powis.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Estate of Powis was owned by the Frasers—their crest is shown on the towers—until the marriage of an heiress to a Leslie.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The house was the home of John Leslie, Professor of Greek at Kings College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was subsequently owned by the Burnett family.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Burnett sold most of the estate to Aberdeen Town Council who built a housing estate in the area comprising over 300 residences.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Sir Duncan Rice Library was designed by Danish architects Schmidt Hammer Lassen and completed in 2011.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was officially opened by Queen Elizabeth II in September 2012 and named after Duncan Rice, a previous Principal of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This seven-storey tower, clad in zebra-like jagged stripes of white and clear glass, replaced the smaller Queen Mother Library as the university's main library and can be seen prominently from the entire campus and much of the city.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is open to the public and outstanding views of the city and coastline are available from the upper floors.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In addition to expanded facilities it also houses public exhibition space and the university's historic collections, comprising more than a quarter of a million ancient and priceless books and manuscripts collected over five centuries since the university's foundations.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Other libraries are in the Taylor Building on the same campus (for law books and materials) and at Foresterhill (for medicine and medical sciences).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's library service (i.e. including all libraries) holds over one million books.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The most recent building is the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Completed in 2021, the building contains laboratories for subjects including biological sciences, chemistry, geosciences and medical sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Aberdeen Sports Village, located across King Street from the Old Aberdeen campus, houses sports facilities and the aquatics centre.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's Foresterhill Campus is located approximately 1.75 kilometres (1.09 mi) to the east of the Old Aberdeen campus and is home to the university's Life Sciences and Medicine facilities.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is co-located with Aberdeen Royal Infirmary, Royal Aberdeen Children's Hospital and Aberdeen Maternity Hospital, all teaching hospitals operated by regional health board NHS Grampian.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The campus accommodates the School of Medicine, Medical Science and Nutrition; the School of Psychology; and the School of Biological Sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It also includes the Rowett Institute of Nutrition and Health, the Institute of Medical Sciences, Institute of Applied Health Sciences, Institute of Dentistry, and Institute of Education for Medical & Dental Sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Foresterhill site is managed jointly with NHS Grampian.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university has had a presence at Foresterhill since around 1938, and the management of the site was formalised in 1997 by the completion of an operational agreement between the two parties.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A new campus in Doha, Qatar was established in May 2017.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Known as AFG College with the University of Aberdeen, it is a partnership with Al Faleh Group for Educational and Academic Services (AFG).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It offers undergraduate and postgraduate programmes in business, law, linguistics, social science, computing science and public health.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Marischal College is a neo-Gothic building, having been rebuilt in 1836–41, and greatly extended several years later.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Formerly an open three-sided court, the college now forms a quadrangle as additions to the buildings were opened by Edward VII in 1906 and form the current facade from Broad Street.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The building is widely considered to be one of the best examples of neo-Gothic architecture in Great Britain; the architect, Alexander Marshall Mackenzie was a native of Aberdeen as well as an alumnus of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Mitchell Tower at the rear is named for the benefactor (Dr Charles Mitchell) who paid for the graduation hall.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The opening of this tower in 1895 was part of celebrations of the 400th anniversary of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Until 1996, Marischal College housed the Departments of Molecular & Cell Biology and Biomedical Sciences, which had been there for many decades.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] From 1996, the departments moved to Kings College campus and Foresterhill campus.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Teaching no longer takes place at Marischal College, with many of the departments formerly based there having moved to King's College some decades previously.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] While graduations and other events (e.g. concerts) took place in the cathedral-like Mitchell Hall in the north wing, for many years much of the building (including the frontage to the street) was derelict.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The majority of the building was leased to Aberdeen City Council in 2008, with significant re-development taking place to allow the council to occupy it as its new administrative headquarters.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Occupation of the rear portion of the building is retained by the university including the former Marischal Museum and Mitchell Hall, which was used previously for graduation and other academic ceremonies before moving to Elphinstone Hall at King's College.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A small campus at Hilton became part of the university estate following a merger in 2001 between the university and the Aberdeen campus of the Northern College of Education, and temporarily became home to the university's Faculty of Education.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was less than a mile southwest of King's College campus.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Following the renovation of the MacRobert Building at King's College to house the School of Education (completed in 2005), the Hilton campus was closed and sold to developers.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The campus was demolished and the land is now occupied by a residential development called "The Campus".
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In common with the other ancient universities in Scotland, the university's structure of governance is largely regulated by the Universities (Scotland) Acts of 1858.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This gives the university a tripartite constitution comprising the General Council of senior academics and graduates, the University Court responsible for finances and administration, and the Academic Senate (*Senatus Academicus*)—the university's supreme academic body.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] There are correspondingly three main officers of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is nominally headed by the chancellor, a largely ceremonial position traditionally held by the Bishop of Aberdeen, but as a result of the Scottish Reformation holders are now elected for life by the General Council.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] There is also a rector of the university, who chairs the University Court and is elected by the students for a three-year term to represent their interests.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] There are also four assessors, ten masters, including the principal and vice principal, and the factor or procurator.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The administrative head and chief executive of the university is its principal and vice-chancellor.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The principal acts as chair of the *Senatus Academicus*, and his status as vice-chancellor enables him to perform the functions reserved to the chancellor in the latter's absence, such as the awarding of degrees.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's three most significant officials are its chancellor, principal, and rector, whose rights and responsibilities are largely derived from the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor is the nominal head of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor since 2013 is Queen Camilla.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] She is the first female chancellor of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The chancellor, or, if necessary, his or her deputy, confers degrees on graduates and chairs the university's General Council.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The principal and vice-chancellor of the university is Professor Peter Edwards, having succeeded George Boyne in November 2025.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Professor Edwards was previously the university's Vice-Principal for Regional Engagement and has been with the university for over 35 years.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The rector of the university has been—since 1860—elected by the students to serve a three-year term of office; before that, the office was appointed.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The rector's duties are to chair meetings of the University Court and to represent student views on that body.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In November 2024, Iona Fyfe, a Scottish folk singer, was elected by the student body of the university as the new rector.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Other notable Aberdeen rectors have included Winston Churchill, Andrew Carnegie, H.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Asquith, Maggie Chapman and Clarissa Dickson Wright, who was Aberdeen's first female rector.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] This body was created by the commissioners during the merger of King's and Marischal in 1870.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It was part of a series of reforms introduced to rectify the method of government, with the Court acting as a court of appeal from the Senatus.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Court originally consisted of six members; the rector, representing the students, the principal, and one assessor each to the chancellor, the rector, the General Council and the Senatus.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] However, today the Court consists of many more members.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Court's principal role is to oversee the management of the revenue, property and other resources of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Academic Senate (Latin: *Senatus Academicus*) is the supreme academic body for the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Its members include all the professors of the university, certain senior readers, a number of senior lecturers and lecturers and elected student senate representatives.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is responsible for authorising degree programmes and issuing all degrees to graduates, and for managing student discipline.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The president of the Senate is the university principal.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is divided into 12 schools which are organised within a broad range of disciplines, with the larger schools sub-divided into three teaching colleges.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Multi-disciplinary institutes and research centres allow the university's experts to collaborate on pioneering research projects.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In the financial year ending 31 July 2024, Aberdeen had a total income of £264 million (2022/23 – £268.6 million) and total expenditure of £188.9 million (2022/23 – £259.3 million).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] At year end, Aberdeen had endowments of £65.3 million (2023 – £58.6 million) and total net assets of £431 million (2023 – £352.4 million).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's coat of arms is an integral part of the current logo, which along with the colours burgundy and white, is used extensively on campus signage, printed materials, and online.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university's coat of arms incorporates those of the founders and locations of the two colleges it is derived from.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In the top left quadrant are the arms of the burgh of Old Aberdeen, with the addition of a symbol of knowledge being handed down from above.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Top right are those of George Keith, the fifth Earl Marischal.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Bottom left are those of Bishop William Elphinstone.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The bottom right quarter is a simplified version of the three castles which represent the city of Aberdeen (this symbol of the city also appears prominently on the arms of The Robert Gordon University).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The motto of the University of Aberdeen is *Initium Sapientiae Timor Domini*, which translates from Latin as "*The beginning of wisdom is fear of the Lord*".
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It is a quote from the Old Testament of the Bible, Psalm 111, verse 10.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] It also appears in the Book of Proverbs (9:10).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The motto can be seen at the archway beside New King's on the High Street at the King's College campus, as well as other campus locations and in formal settings such as on graduation certificates.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A university tartan was created in 1992 as part of the celebrations for the 500th anniversary of the university which took place in 1995.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The tartan was designed by the Weavers Incorporation of Aberdeen and Harry Lindley and incorporates colours from the university's coat of arms.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Academic dress has been worn in the University of Aberdeen since mediaeval times.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen shared with the other ancient universities the wearing of scarlet gowns (*toga rubra*) and a trencher for undergraduates, but by the middle of the twentieth century its use amongst the students had faded.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Bursars formerly wore a black gown, and were made to perform menial services about college.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Female students wore a trencher with scarlet tassels, while male students wore black tassels.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Academic dress is usually worn only at formal occasions, such as at graduation, Founder's Day, or academic processions which take place for ceremonial reasons.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] MA, BSc, LLB etc.), a long black gown is worn with a hood of black silk and lined with silk in a colour which varies depending on discipline.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] For example, the lining is white silk for all Master of Arts degrees, green silk for Bachelor of Science in pure sciences, and crimson silk for MBChB.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] MSc, MLitt etc.) a long black gown is worn, with a white silk hood lined in a colour that varies by discipline.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] For PhD, the doctor's scarlet robe is worn with black facings and sleeve lining, along with a black "John Knox" cap.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] EdD, LLD etc.), the scarlet robe has facings and sleeve linings in a different colour.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The academic year at Aberdeen was originally based upon the Scottish Term and Quarter Days, beginning with Martinmas (October – November), Candlemas (January – March), and ending with Whitsunday (April – June).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] However, today the academic term is divided into two semesters, the First Half-Session and the Second-Half Session, beginning in September and ending in May.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Written examinations are sat in November and April and May, and graduation is celebrated either in November or at the end of June.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen was ranked 119th in the world in *TIME* magazine's 2026 ranking of the world's top universities.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In 2025, Aberdeen was consistently ranked among the top 250 universities in the world and consistently ranked within the top 25 universities in the United Kingdom by *The Guardian* and *The Times*.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 2019 *Times Higher Education University Impact Rankings*, Aberdeen was ranked 31st in the world for impact on society.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Over 75 per cent of the university's research was classified as 'world leading' or 'internationally excellent' in the 2014 Research Excellence Framework.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Its highest internationally ranked subject is Divinity and Religious Studies, which is ranked at joint 25th in the world and 7th in the UK.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Economics was ranked 11th in the UK by Times Subject Rankings and 12th in the UK by Complete University Guide 2019.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In 2022, the university formed an international university alliance with the University of Calgary in Alberta, Canada and Curtin University in Perth, Australia to address global challenges together.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The alliance provides joint research centres, collaborative academic programs, industry linkage, and student and staff mobility exchanges.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is a member of the University of the Arctic and participates in its mobility program, north2north, which enables students of member institutions to study in different parts of the North.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] In the 2024/25 academic year, the student body consisted of 13,930 students, composed of 9,815 undergraduates and 4,115 postgraduate students.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is designated as a 'medium-tariff' institution by the Department for Education, with the average undergraduate entrant to the university in recent years amassing between 122–130 UCAS Tariff points in their top three pre-university qualifications.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Based on 2022/23 HESA entry standards data published in domestic league tables, which include a broad range of qualifications beyond the top three exam grades, the average student at the University of Aberdeen achieved 184 points – the tenth highest in the United Kingdom.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university has one of the smallest percentages of students from lower-class backgrounds, being ranked fifth from bottom for class equality.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university participates in widening access schemes such as the Children's University, REACH Scotland, Access Aberdeen, and ASPIRENorth, in order to promote a more widespread uptake of those traditionally under-represented at university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Gifford Lectures, established in 1887 by Adam Gifford, began at the university (along with the other ancient universities in Scotland) with E.B Tylor's lecture on the Natural History of Religion between 1889 and 1891.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] Since then, over 30 Gifford Lectures have been given at the university, with some distinguished figures including Hannah Arendt, Alfred North Whitehead, Karl Barth, Paul Tillich, Michael Polanyi, N.T.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] A public lecture series was held in 2011 to commemorate the 400th anniversary of the publication of the King's James Bible.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The university is also host to the annual Andrew Carnegie Lecture Series which began in 2014, with the first lecture given by Matthew Barzun.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p01] The Elphinstone Institute hosts its own monthly lecture series, which began in 2016, in the MacRobert Building, with lectures usually given on local or Scottish topics.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The library was first located in the nave of King's College Chapel and then moved to a new site in the college in 1870.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The current library contains one of the most extensive university library collections in the United Kingdom, with over a million volumes and a quarter of a million ancient and priceless books and manuscripts, including the Hortus sanitatis.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The library at Aberdeen was given the right of legal deposit under the Statute of Anne (1710) but this was rescinded in 1837, and as a result has a rare collection of pre-Victorian novels.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The core of the original library at King's College was formed from Elphinstone's books that he left to the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The books were originally housed in a room in the south east tower (now the round tower).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] They were then moved to a building on the south side of Kings College Chapel, and in 1773 to the west end of the chapel.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] They were located in 1870 to a new building as illustrated.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] This library was extended in 1885, with galleries being installed in 1912, reading desks in 1932 and a mezzanine floor in 1964.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Queen Mother Library had been the university's main library since 1965, and the original library in King's College was replaced with the King's College Conference Centre in 1991.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Queen Mother Library was refurbished and expanded in 1982.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Sir Duncan Rice Library was officially opened on 24 September 2012 by Her Majesty Queen Elizabeth accompanied by the Duke of Edinburgh, replacing the Queen Mother Library.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It was designed by the Danish architectural firm Schmidt Hammer Lassen at the cost of £57 million.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The building sits on a base of Scottish stone.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The ground floor is double-height with seven floors above.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The building is clad in zebra-like jagged stripes of white and clear glass.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In the interior void spaces are located centrally.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Contrasting with the geometric exterior, the central atrium formed by the void spaces has an organic form, shifting in location across the levels.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It has won numerous awards for its architecture.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university also has the Taylor Law Library which is located in the Taylor Building in Old Aberdeen, and the Medical Library on the Foresterhill Campus, which covers the Medicine and Medical Sciences disciplines.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Christ's College also possesses its own Divinity library.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university maintains several museums and galleries, open free to the public.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university's collections are internationally renowned and are recognised as of national significance by the Scottish Government.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Originating in the eighteenth century, they now have over 300,000 items across a wide range of Human Culture, Medicine and Health, and Natural History.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Zoology Museum is officially classified as a Recognised Collection of national significance to Scotland and features displays from protozoa to the great whales, including taxidermy, skeletal material, study skins, fluid-preserved specimens and models.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] As of 2024/25 the university had 13,930 students, of which 4,115 were postgraduates.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2009/10 students represented 120 countries with about 46% men, 54% women.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Of all of undergraduates, 19% were mature students (i.e. aged 25 years or more).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university has more than 550 different undergraduate degree programmes and more than 120 postgraduate taught programmes.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The student body is represented by a students' association known as Aberdeen University Students' Association (AUSA).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Additionally, the elected Rector of the University of Aberdeen serves along with the AUSA president and another sabbatical officer as students' representatives on the University Court.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] AUSA does not operate a traditional students' union, instead operating out of a university building, The Students Union Building, formerly The Hub, helping to support students and provide events and studying space.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] A large students' union formerly occupied a granite building on the corner of Gallowgate and Upperkirkgate in the city centre, opposite Marischal College, but it closed in 2003.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] A second, smaller union opened at nearby Littlejohn Street a couple of years later, but by 2010 it too had closed.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The organisation has been involved in the creation of "The Hub", a university-owned dining and social centre created by an extensive renovation of the former Central Refectory at the King's College campus.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It provides facilities for the whole university community (students and staff) and opened in 2006.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] A more traditional social space, the Butchart Student Centre, opened in 2009.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It acts as the HQ of the Students' Association and provides a wide range of student facilities, but due to city council licensing regulations there is no bar.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Butchart Centre includes facilities for student societies and offices.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Butchart Centre was converted from what had been the campus sports centre before the opening of the Aberdeen Sports Village nearby.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] AUSA operates out of the Johnston Building.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] "BookEnds" which sells second-hand books with profits going towards charity was initially established in the Butchart Recreation Centre but now operates in the AUSA building.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] There are over a hundred clubs and societies formally affiliated with the students' association.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The students' association is responsible for sport at the university, which is managed by the Aberdeen University Sports Union, an AUSA committee.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] All registered students are eligible to join any of these clubs or societies.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university's oldest student organisation is the Aberdeen University Debater, founded by JF Maclennan in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1871, a Literary Society was started by WM Ramsay, and four years later a Choral Society came to life.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1884, the society also took the first steps towards the introduction of a students' representative council under support from Alexander Bain, the then Rector.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The creation of the Union in 1895 provided a new debating chamber in Marischal College and the society's first permanent home.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The chamber beneath Mitchell Hall in Marischal College is Scotland's oldest purpose-built debating chamber.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 1998, an alumni fund called the Aberdeen Future Fund was founded, run by the Development Trust.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It has raised over £2.5 million of unrestricted funds.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Past projects have included a book fund for the Heavy Demand section in the library, providing "Safe Campus" leaflets, contributing to the student hardship fund, providing training mannequins for Clinical Skills, the organ for King's College Chapel, and funding for intramural sports.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Established in 1889, it is affiliated to the BUCS and SSS and encompasses over fifty sports clubs.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] There are large playing fields at the back of King's College and also Aberdeen Sports Village, a partnership between the University of Aberdeen, Aberdeen City Council and sportscotland.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] An extension containing the aquatics centre opened on 5 May 2014.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen University Football Club was formed in 1872, and currently competes in the SJFA North First Division.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen University Rugby Football Club was founded in 1871, and has a long history of producing both Scottish and British Lions players.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The annual boat race between Aberdeen University Boat Club and Robert Gordon University Boat Club has been competed for since 1995.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The University of Aberdeen has lost only four times, in 2006, 2009, 2012 and 2013.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Aberdeen Sports Village served as one of the official pre-games training venues of the Cameroon Olympic Team prior to the London 2012 Olympic Games.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] There are a large number of ensembles at the University of Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Some are directed by academic staff, while others are run by students both in and out of the department and include; Balinese Gamelan, Baroque Ensemble, Big Band, Cantores ad Portam, Chapel Choir, Choral Society, Concert Band, String Orchestra and Symphony Orchestra.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show is a musical and theatrical show, usually with a strong comedy element, staged every year since 1921.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Its purpose is to raise money for charity, as part of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] A number of its writers, performers and musicians have gone on to greater renown in the fields of theatre, media and the arts.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The first successful university newspaper, *Alma Mater*, began under the auspices of the University of Aberdeen Debating Society in 1883.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The *Alma Mater* was replaced by *The Gaudie*, which has been in circulation since 1934, and is currently free-of-charge.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] *The Gaudie* is recognised as one of the oldest student newspapers in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The University of Aberdeen also hosts a chapter of Her Campus, a magazine targeted at female students that publishes yearly magazines showcasing society member's written work.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Other student media organisations include Granite City TV and Aberdeen Student Radio (ASR).
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Although these have both become inactive.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the university's WORD Centre for Creative Writing.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] It has featured notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Until 2019, each year a student-led torcher parade was held.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] First held in 1889, it was the largest of its kind in Europe.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Student groups and societies build floats and parade in fancy dress through the city centre to raise money for local charities.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Traditionally spectators donated money in the form of coppers, a colloquial term for 1p and 2p coins.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Halls of residence are managed by the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Two large concentrations of university accommodation are provided on the campus in Old Aberdeen and one mile north at the Hillhead Student Village, accessible by a walk through Seaton Park.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Campus accommodation in the heart of Old Aberdeen consists of self-catered King's Hall and Elphinstone Road Halls.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university has a "First-Year Accommodation Guarantee" providing that the student accept their firm offer before a set date prior to the beginning of term.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] In 2014–15, the university ran out of rooms and had to resort to temporary accommodation.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The university continues to monitor accommodation costs and where possible offers discretionary support to students, to improve access to higher education.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The first modern halls of residence built by the university on the King's College campus was Crombie halls, named after James Edward Crombie.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Crombie-Johnston halls were closed in 2017 following a decline in demand for catered accommodation.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Elphinstone Road halls were completed in 1992.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The Sponsio Academica is the oath, originally in Latin, taken by students matriculating into the four ancient Scottish universities (Edinburgh, St.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] This tradition now has been digitised at Aberdeen and is agreed to as part of an online matriculation process.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Originally, new students matriculated in Mitchell Hall where the Chancellor would give a welcoming address.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Usually held annually in February, on Founders' Day, the university community pays tribute to its historic origins as an ancient university and in particular, the role played by William Elphinstone and other benefactors in the establishment of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The ceremony begins with an academic procession through the university and concludes with a service in King's College Chapel.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Talks are given by university lecturers and invited guests.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] A candle is lit in the chapel to give thanks to Elphinstone and the other patron fathers.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The rector, an ancient post dating back to the foundation of the university in 1495, is the students' representative, particularly in welfare matters, and sits on the University Court.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Tradition dictates that the University of Aberdeen's new rector must ride through Old Aberdeen aloft a bull carried at shoulder height by students of the university.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The ceremony includes a colourful academic procession representing civic, student and academic life in Aberdeen.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] University staff and students, along with representatives from the City and Aberdeenshire Councils, Incorporated Trades, MSPs, and alumni, attend the ceremony which is followed by a reception in the King's Conference Centre.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] The reception culminates with the new Rector being carried by the student mascot, Angus the Bull, from King's College to the St Machar Bar in the High Street of Old Aberdeen, where tradition also dictates that they buy a round of drinks for their student supporters.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Bajan, a medieval term (literally 'yellow beak' – bec jaune), describing trainees in the pre-student year, was traditionally applied to the university's first year undergraduates.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Female undergraduates were referred to as "bajanellas".
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Second year students were called 'Semis', and these usually played jokes upon or clashed with bajans.
[src:arnold-hague/aberdeen-university-p02] Semis would usually tear first year's gowns.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:arnold-hague/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:arnold-hague/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:arnold-hague/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:arnold-hague/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:arnold-hague/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:arnold-hague/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:arnold-hague/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:arnold-hague/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] Hague was born December 3, 1840, in Boston, Massachusetts, to William Hague, a clergyman.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He graduated from Sheffield Scientific School at Yale University in 1863.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He then spent three years in Germany, studying at the universities of Göttingen and Heidelberg, and at the Freiberg Mining Academy.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] In 1867 he returned to the United States, and was appointed assistant geologist on the U.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] S. geological exploration of the 40th parallel under Clarence King.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] In Volume II—“Descriptive Geology”—of the report of the exploration, which was the joint work of Hague and Samuel F.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] Emmons, there is given the results of a detailed geological survey across the Cordilleras of North America, from the Great Plains to the Sierra Nevada range in California.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] This work included a geological atlas of maps and sections, which was completed after a great deal of hardship, the map of the Great Basin being accomplished before the completion of either the Union or Central Pacific Railroad.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] On the termination of this work in 1877, he received the appointment of government geologist of Guatemala, and traveled extensively over the republic, visiting the principal mining regions and the canters of volcanic activity.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] In 1878 he was engaged by the Chinese government to examine gold, silver, and lead mines in northern China.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] Geological Survey in 1879, he returned to the United States, and became one of its geologists.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He was sent to Nevada, and made a report on the “Geology of the Eureka District.” In 1883 he was made geologist of the Yellowstone Park division, and assigned to the study of the geysers of that district in connection with the extinct volcanic regions of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He was a member of scientific societies both in the United States and Europe and in 1885 was elected to the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He received an Sc.D. degree from Columbia University in 1901, and an LL.D. degree from Aberdeen University.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] In 1903, he was elected to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He was a member of the commission appointed by the National Academy of Sciences at the request of the United States Government in 1896 to prepare plans for the National Forest preserves.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He was vice president of the International Congresses of Geologists held in Paris in 1900, in Stockholm in 1910 and in Toronto in 1913.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] He became president of the Geological Society of America in 1910.
[src:arnold-hague/arnold-hague] Hague died May 14, 1917, in Washington, D.C.
